 order to further elite goals. Ultimately, Downey lays out a path for environmental social scientists and environmentalists to better understand and help solve the world’s myriad social and environmental crises. Inequality, Democracy and the Environment presents a passionate exposé of the true role inequality, undemocratic institutions and organizational power play in harming people and the environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental degradationxSocial aspects. 0aEnvironmental justice. 0aEnvironmental policyxDecision making. 0aEnvironmental policyxSocial aspects. 0aEnvironmental sociology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479850723.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479885978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479885978/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles